Fig. 2b shows the fluorescence spectra of the four materials when excited at 365 nm, while afterglow spectra acquired after the extinction of the UV light source are presented in Fig. 2c. Combining with the photographic images presented in Fig. 2g, the C-SiNDs@UA appears white in daylight, emits blue light when UV-irradiated, and exhibits a cyan afterglow when the UV light is extinguished, with fluorescence and phosphorescence maxima observed at 425 and 520 nm, respectively. Y-SiNDs@UA appears yellowish in daylight, emits blue light when irradiated with UV light, and shows a yellow afterglow when the UV source is extinguished, with fluorescence and phosphorescence maxima at 450 and 555 nm, respectively. Fluorescence and afterglow emissions were also examined when excited at various wavelengths to determine the complete spectral properties of the developed materials (
   Fig. S10,S11
). It can be seen that the fluorescence and phosphorescence of both C-SiNDs@UA and Y-SiNDs@UA exhibit excitation-dependent behaviors. The excitation-dependent fluorescence is caused by the distribution of different emission sites of silicon nanodots. FT-IR and XPS characterization results demonstrate the existence of different kinds of surface functional groups in silicon nanodots, which give rise to a series of energy levels and result in a range of emission centers [44]. At a specific excitation wavelength, a dominant emission site is activated, resulting in a characteristic emission spectrum. Notably, as the excitation wavelength is tuned, the corresponding dominant emission center undergoes a remarkable shift, revealing the remarkable excitation-dependent properties of these fascinating nanomaterials [45–47]. The phosphorescence phenomena are closely related to the fluorescence property. When excited by excitation light, singlet excitons are converted into triplet excitons through intersystem crossing. With the presence of multiple emissive centers, singlet excitons generated under different excitations can activate different triplet excitons, leading to the alteration of the dominant emission centers [48–50]. At the same time, the presence of hydrogen bonds can suppress the nonradiative transition and further stabilize the triplet excitons in different states, which eventually leads to the excitation-dependent phosphorescence phenomena [51,52]. The fluorescence and phosphorescence emission peaks of these two materials exhibit color shifts that are beneficial for subsequent anti-counterfeiting applications. O-SiNDs@UA appears light orange in daylight, emits orange light under UV irradiation and shows an orange afterglow when the UV light is removed, with fluorescence and afterglow maxima observed at 575 and 575 nm, respectively. On the other hand, R-SiNDs@UA is soft-red in daylight, emits red light when UV irradiated, and exhibits red afterglow following removal of the UV light, with fluorescence and afterglow maxima at 602 and 605 nm, respectively. Intriguingly, the fluorescence and afterglow bands of these two materials overlap and were unaffected by the excitation wavelength (
   Fig. S10,S11
); these observations tentatively confirm the presence of P-FRET. Rh 6G and Rh B are excited by the light source and SiNDs@UA when UV-irradiated, and are also excited by the SiNDs@UA afterglow following removal of the excitation source and continue to emit light [30]. The Commission Internationale Eclairage (CIE) diagram (Fig. 2d) shows the coordinates of the four phosphorescent colors, which are consistent with the naked-eye observations. These four easily distinguishable colors, which are observed when excited at the same wavelength, are important prerequisites for increasing the range of materials for use in practical applications.

The fluorescence and phosphorescence lifetime data were fitted using exponential-decay calculations, with the resulting equations listed in supplementary material. The fluorescence lifetimes of C-, Y-, O-, and R-SiNDs@UA (Fig. 2e) were calculated to be 5.03 ns, 7.02 ns, 5.82 ns, and 4.95 ns, respectively, with the fluorescence quantum yields of 21.43 %, 16.57 %, 83.25 %, and 72.64 %, respectively. More importantly, satisfactory phosphorescence lifetimes were observed, with 562 and 546 ms determined for C-SiNDs@UA and Y-SiNDs@UA, respectively, and 495 and 481 ms measured for O-SiNDs@UA and R-SiNDs@UA (Fig. 2f), respectively. The abovementioned four materials exhibited phosphorescence quantum yields of 13.80 %, 24.22 %, 9.83 % and 14.92 %, respectively. Fig. 2g shows afterglows observed by the naked eye after extinguishing the 365 nm excitation source, with C-, Y-, O-, and R-SiNDs@UA showing afterglow durations of 13, 12, 8, and 6 s, respectively. The four materials developed in this study show multi-color afterglows and/or longer lifetimes than those of previously reported materials, which are advantages that demonstrate their applications potentials (
                           Table S4
                        ).
